{"title_page": "The Chain Gang of 1974", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = The Chain Gang of 1974\n| image               = The Chain Gang of 1974 2014.jpg\n| image_size          = \n| caption             = Mohager performing in 2014\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Kamtin Karimi Mohager\n| alias               = The Chain Gang of 1974\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1985|7|31}}\n| birth_place         = [[San Jose, California]], US\n| origin              = \n| genre               = {{flatlist|\n* [[Indietronica]]\n* [[Electronic music|electronic]]\n* [[synth-pop]]\n* [[indie pop]]\n* [[alternative rock]]\n}}\n| occupation          = {{flatlist|\n* Musician\n* songwriter\n* composer\n}}\n| instrument          = \n| years_active        = 2007\u2013present\n| label               = {{flatlist|\n* [[Warner Music Group|Warner]] (2012\u20132014)\n* Modern Art\n}}\n| associated_acts     = [[Teenage Wrist]]\n| website             = \n}}\n\n'''The Chain Gang of 1974''' is the [[indietronica]] project of American musician and DJ, '''Kamtin Mohager'''. \"The Chain Gang of 1974\" can also be in reference to Kamtin Mohager himself. Mohager was raised in Hawaii and [[Colorado]], and currently lives in Los Angeles, California.\n\n==History==\nBorn in [[San Jose, California]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/2014/03/06/sxsw-music-picks-chain-gang-of-1974-buzzes-into-texas/|title=SXSW Music Picks: Chain Gang of 1974 buzzes into Texas|date=2014-03-06|website=The Mercury News|access-date=2017-08-01}}</ref> and raised in Hawaii (before moving to [[Denver]]), Kamtin Mohager (Nato) joined [[3OH!3]] as a touring bassist from 2008 through 2010. He self-released ''Fantastic Nostalgic: The Early Recordings'' in 2010. That year also saw the release of his full-length debut, ''White Guts''. Mohager moved to Los Angeles to record the follow-up album, ''Wayward Fire'', which was released on Modern Art Records in 2011.<ref name=\"Cherrie\">\n{{cite web\n| last=Cherrie\n| first=Chrysta \n| url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/the-chain-gang-of-1974-mn0001035500/biography\n| title=The Chain Gang of 1974 \u2013 Biography\n| website=[[Allmusic]]\n| accessdate=October 2, 2013\n}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2010, Mohager combined both early EP's into a digital-only release titled 'Fantastic Nostalgic: The Early Recordings. Mohager describes his early sound as \"all over the place, from a piano ballad to songs that sound like [[Black Rebel Motorcycle Club]], [[Primal Scream]], or [[Justice (band)|Justice]].\"<ref name=\"Fairbanks\">\n{{cite web\n| url=https://www.npr.org/2011/12/22/144067881/the-chain-gang-of-1974-on-world-cafe\n| title=The Chain Gang of 1974 on World Cafe\n| publisher=[[NPR]]\n| date=December 22, 2011\n| accessdate=October 2, 2013\n}}</ref> Zachary Houle of ''[[PopMatters]]'' called the album \"an homage to the '80s, in particular, the soundtracks to John Hughes films, and it is, in a word, fun.\"<ref name=\"Houle\">\n{{cite magazine\n| last=Houle\n| first=Zachary\n| url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/144925-the-chain-gang-of-1974-wayward-fire/\n| title=Review: The Chain Gang of 1974 \u2013 'Wayward Fire'\n| magazine=[[PopMatters]]\n| date=July 27, 2011\n| accessdate=October 2, 2013\n}}</ref> [[Pitchfork Media]]'s Ian Cohen remarked that it \"ends up less like a living celebration of the past and more like a display case of your favorite synth-pop action figures in their original packaging.\"<ref name=\"Cohen\">\n{{cite web\n| last=Cohen\n| first=Ian\n| url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/15644-wayward-fire/\n| title=Reviews: The Chain Gang of 1974 \u2013 'Wayward Fire'\n| publisher=[[Pitchfork Media]]\n| date=July 14, 2011\n| accessdate=October 2, 2013\n}}</ref> David Marchese of ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' wrote that the album \"swoons and grooves deliciously, but the lyrics have a distinctly processed flavor\".<ref name=\"Marchese\">\n{{cite journal \n| date=July 2011\n| last=Marchese\n| first=David\n| title=Reviews: Albums: The Chain Gang of 1974 \u2013 'Wayward Fire'\n| journal=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]\n| publisher=SPIN Media LLC\n| volume=27\n| issue=6\n| pages=70\u20131\n| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HjzFlV6oDIQC&pg=PA70&dq=%22chain+gang+of+1974%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=XHFMUvSLJuWiigLS6oC4Dg&ved=0CEIQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=%22chain%20gang%20of%201974%22&f=false\n| accessdate=October 2, 2013\n| issn=0886-3032}}</ref> Max Blau of ''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]'' called it \"one of the better and most cohesive electronic albums\" of 2011.<ref name=\"Blau\">\n{{cite magazine\n| last=Blau \n| first=Max\n| url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2011/06/best-of-whats-next-the-chain-gang-of-1974.html\n| title=Best of What's Next: The Chain Gang of 1974\n| magazine=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]\n| date=June 20, 2011\n| accessdate=October 2, 2013\n}}</ref> [[Allmusic]]'s William Ruhlmann said: \"Mohager convincingly makes the case that there is more to say in the music of the '80s, even if fashion has banished it to its own radio formats and nostalgia tours.\"<ref name=\"Ruhlmann\">\n{{cite web\n| last=Ruhlmann\n| first=William \n| url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/wayward-fire-mw0002137234\n| title=Album Review: The Chain Gang of 1974 \u2013 'Wayward Fire'\n| website=Allmusic\n| accessdate=October 2, 2013\n}}</ref> Justin Gerber of ''[[Consequence of Sound]]'' found flaws in the lyrics and suggested that \"just about every song could be cut by about a minute\", but added that \"nearly every song has a beat that pummels you into submission, and that is most definitely a compliment.\"<ref name=\"Gerber\">\n{{cite magazine\n| last=Gerber\n| first=Justin\n| url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2011/06/album-review-the-chain-gang-of-1974-wayward-fire/\n| title=Album Review: The Chain Gang of 1974 \u2013 'Wayward Fire'\n| magazine=[[Consequence of Sound]]\n| date=June 21, 2011\n| accessdate=October 2, 2013\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Mohager signed to [[Warner Music Group]] for the release of his third full-length album, ''[[Daydream Forever]]''. The album is described as a continuation of the synth-heavy, reverb-laden dreams that made Mohager\u2019s debut album, Wayward Fire, an immediate favorite of the retro set. Production is thicker here, with more elastic bounces. If that means it feels like you\u2019ve stepped into a 1980s night at the local bar (as one reviewer humorously put it), then Mohager has clearly succeeded. This is the guy who wasn\u2019t moved to make music until hearing [[Tears for Fears]] in the movie ''[[Real Genius]]'', says the legend; when tracks such as \u201cOrdinary Fools,\u201d \u201cYou,\u201d \u201cMoksha,\" and \u201cDeath Metal Punk\u201d hit you firmly across the ears with their indelible 1980s-styled hooks, everything is working according to his lo-hi-tech plans. Elements of [[Tears for Fears]], [[Duran Duran]], OMD, and [[M83 (band)|M83]] coalesce into a party of their own. \u201cPlum\u201d ends things on a slightly darker Prefab Sprout\u2013style tone.\n\nIn 2013, Mohager received worldwide recognition when his song \u201cSleepwalking\u201d was featured on the soundtrack of ''[[Grand Theft Auto V]]'', as well as on the game's official trailer.\n\nIn summer 2014, Mohager teamed up with DJ/producer [[Dillon Francis]], as well as [[Sultan & Ned Shepard]] for the release of \"When We Were Young\".<ref>{{youtube|95-cScAf_40|When We Were Young}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2015, Mohager launched a collaborative side project with Marshall Gallagher of [[Swing Hero]] titled \"[[Teenage Wrist]]\". The band's debut single \"Afterglow\" received praise from [[My Chemical Romance]] frontman [[Gerard Way]].\n\n===2016\u20132018: ''Felt''===\nOn September 9, 2016, The Chain Gang of 1974 released his single \"I Still Wonder\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=r9rh7wI3BRE |title=The Chain Gang of 1974 - I Still Wonder - YouTube |publisher=YouTube.com |date=September 9, 2016 |accessdate=2016-12-01}}</ref> On March 26, 2017, The Chain Gang of 1974 announced the release of his new album, ''[[Felt (The Chain Gang of 1974 album)|Felt]]'', which was released on June 23 through Caroline Records.\n\n===2019-Present: ''Pollen & Upcoming Album''===\nOn February 15, 2019, The Chain Gang of 1974 released the single \u201cBurn Out\u201d along with the announcement that he would be releasing one single per month throughout 2019. Then, on March 22, 2019, Mohager released \u201cHeaven\u201d, produced by [[Chadwick Johnson]] of the band Hundreth. The next month on April 26 followed the release of the third single, \u201cSuch A Shame.\u201d Mohager later stated on [[Twitter]] that the track was inspired by [[Jimmy Eat World]]. On May 24, The Chain Gang of 1974 released the fourth single \u201cOrdinary Fools, Pt. 2\u201d, the follow up to the [[Daydream Forever]] opening track \u201cOrdinary Fools\u201d. On June 21, Mohager released the track \u201cYDLMA\u201d (You Don\u2019t Love Me Anymore). The next month on July 26 saw the release\nOf \u201cFrom Here Who Knows\u201d. This was the last monthly single, and there was not another single in August. Instead of releasing a single in August, Mohager instead announces an upcoming [[Extended play|EP]] entitled \u201cPollen\u201d. The album would consist of the earlier singles \u201cHeaven\u201d, \u201cBurn Out\u201d, and \u201cOrdinary Fools, Pt. 2\u201d, along with a new song titled \u201cHide Tonight\u201d. The EP was released September 6, 2019. Later next month, Mohager announced a new album, and also stated the album would be coming sometime in 2020. The album title is still unknown, but the word \u201cHoney\u201d can be seen as part of the album title in Mohager\u2019s [[Instagram]] story. The album will have 12 tracks, and the remaining singles that weren\u2019t on the \u201cPollen\u201d EP would be included on the album. \u201cSuch A Shame\u201d, \u201cYDLMA\u201d, and \u201cFrom Here Who Knows\u201d. Also, Mohager released \u201c20:25\u201d, a collaborative Single with [[Flux Pavillon]] and [[whatsonot]].\n\n==Tour history==\nThe Chain Gang of 1974 has toured alongside bands, including [[AFI (band)|AFI]], [[Foster the People]], [[The Naked and Famous]], [[Washed Out]], [[Cibo Matto]], [[ABC (band)|ABC]], [[Big Audio Dynamite]], [[Tapes 'n Tapes]], [[Empires (band)|Empires]], [[Sir Sly]], [[Miniature Tigers]], and [[Geographer (band)|Geographer]].\n\n* [[Monolith Festival]] (2008)\n* [[Lollapalooza]] (2011)\n* [[Governors Ball Music Festival]] (2014)\n* [[Austin City Limits Music Festival]] (2014)\n* [[Capitol Hill Block Party]] (2014)\n* [[Free Press Summer Fest]] (2014)\n\n==Touring members==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n*Adam Halferty - drums, bass <small>(2008, 2011)</small>\n*Brandon Anamier \u2013 drums <small>(2008\u20132013)</small>\n*Justin Renaud \u2013 guitar <small>(2010\u20132011, 2016)</small>\n*Tyler Venter \u2013 bass <small>(2010\u20132011)</small>\n*Michael Spear \u2013 bass <small>(2011)</small>\n*Jeff Appruzzese - bass <small>(2011)</small>\n*Xander Singh - bass <small>(2011)</small>\n*Rob Pera - guitar, bass <small>(2011-2012)</small>\n*Jacob Bond \u2013 guitar <small>(2011\u20132014)</small>\n*Sam Tiger \u2013 bass <small>(2012\u20132014)</small>\n*Luc Laurent \u2013 drums <small>(2013\u20132014)</small>\n*Eric Halvorsen \u2013 bass <small>(2016-2017)</small>\n*Mike Robinson \u2013 drums <small>(2016-2017)</small>\n*Troupe Gammage - guitar <small>(2017)</small>\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Discography==\n* ''The Dirt EP'' (February 24, 2007)\n* ''When The Apple Drops - EP'' (January 16, 2008)\n* ''Fantastic Nostalgic: The Early Recordings'' (January 31, 2010)\n* ''White Guts'' (April 27, 2010)\n* ''Wayward Fire'' (June 21, 2011)\n* ''[[Daydream Forever]]'' (February 4, 2014)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/CHAINGANGOF1974/status/404683389644464128 |title=Twitter / CHAINGANGOF1974: New album//DAYDREAM |publisher=Twitter.com |date=November 24, 2013 |accessdate=2014-02-04}}</ref>\n* ''[[Felt (The Chain Gang of 1974 album)|Felt]]'' (June 23, 2017)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/CHAINGANGOF1974/status/845314050837774336 |title=Twitter / CHAINGANGOF1974: the new album FELT |publisher=Twitter.com |date=March 24, 2017 |accessdate=2017-03-25}}</ref>\n* ''Pollen - EP'' (September 6, 2019)\n\n==Songs in media==\n* Song \"Make My Body\" featured in ''[[Scream 4]]'' (2011).\n* Song \"Hold On\" featured in ''[[FIFA 12]]'' (2011).\n* Song \"Devil Is a Lady\" featured in ''[[FIFA Street (2012 video game)|FIFA Street]]'' (2012) and ''[[MLB 12: The Show]]'' (2012).\n* Song \"Undercover\" featured in ''[[FIFA Street (2012 video game)|FIFA Street]]'' (2012).\n* Song \"[[Sleepwalking (The Chain Gang of 1974 song)|Sleepwalking]]\" featured in ''[[Grand Theft Auto V]]'': The Official Trailer, can be heard in the game itself as radio music, and on the [[The Music of Grand Theft Auto V|official soundtrack]]. In addition to this, \"Sleepwalking\" is symbolically played as the end game credits theme for one of the game's three endings, mainly ending \"B\" (2013).\n* Song \"Miko\" featured in ''[[FIFA 14]]'' (2013).\n* Song \"You\" featured in ''[[Real World: Ex-Plosion]]'' (2014).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1243955/|title=The Shortcut (2009) |publisher=IMDb|accessdate=December 27, 2009}}\n*{{cite news|url=http://www.coloradodaily.com/ci_13125380|title=Club Notes: Back on the Chain Gang|last=Kale|first=Wendy |date=June 17, 2009|work=Colorado Daily|accessdate=December 27, 2009}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://clubnotes.pmpblogs.com/colorado-bands/chain-gang-of-1974-playing-bass-wi/|title=The Chain Gang of 1974: Playing Bass with 3OH!3 and Making Waves with Solo Project|last=Kale|first=Wendy |date=June 18, 2009|work=Colorado Daily Blogs|accessdate=December 27, 2009}}\n*{{cite news|url=http://www.kaffeinebuzz.com/interviews-the-chain-gang-of-1974.php|title=The Chain Gang of 1974 \u2013 playing Sunday, Sept 14, 1:30PM, GigBot Stage|last=Owens|first=Kim|date=September 12, 2008|work=Kaffeine Buzz|accessdate=December 27, 2009}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://royalflushmagazine.com/2009/01/22/3oh3-innerpartysystem-chaingang1974/|title=3OH!3, Inner Party System and The Chain Gang of 1974|last=Nubi|first=Lil|date=January 22, 2009|work=Royal Flush|accessdate=December 27, 2009}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/denver/events/white-tie-affair-every-avenue-stereo-skyline-runne,125061/|title=The White Tie Affair|date=November 20, 2009 |publisher=A. V. Club Denver/Boulder|accessdate=December 27, 2009}}{{refend}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.rockstarnetwork.net/2014/04/the-chain-gang-of-1974/|title=Chain Gang of 1974 \u2013 Dream Forever Interview|date=April 27, 2014 |publisher=Rockstarnetwork.net|accessdate=April 27, 2014}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.myspace.com/thechaingangof1974 The Chain Gang of 1974 MySpace page]\n*[http://www.thechaingangof1974.com/ The Chain Gang of 1974 website]\n\n{{The Chain Gang of 1974}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chain Gang of 1974, The}}\n[[Category:Musical groups from Denver]]\n[[Category:Synth-pop musicians]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2007]]\n[[Category:2007 establishments in Colorado]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = The Chain Gang of 1974\n| image               = The Chain Gang of 1974 2014.jpg\n| image_size          = \n| caption             = Mohager performing in 2014\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Kamtin Karimi Mohager\n| alias               = The Chain Gang of 1974\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1985|7|31}}\n| birth_place         = [[San Jose, California]], US\n| origin              = \n| genre               = {{flatlist|\n* [[Indietronica]]\n* [[Electronic music|electronic]]\n* [[synth-pop]]\n* [[indie pop]]\n* [[Alternative rock|alternative]]\n}}\n| occupation          = {{flatlist|\n* Musician\n* songwriter\n* composer\n}}\n| instrument          = \n| years_active        = 2007\u2013present\n| label               = {{flatlist|\n* [[Warner Music Group|Warner]] (2012\u20132014)\n* Modern Art\n}}\n| associated_acts     = [[Teenage Wrist]]\n| website             = \n}}\n\n'''The Chain Gang of 1974''' is the [[indietronica]] project of American musician and DJ, '''Kamtin Mohager'''. \"The Chain Gang of 1974\" can also be in reference to Kamtin Mohager himself. Mohager was raised in Hawaii and [[Colorado]], and currently lives in Los Angeles, California.\n\n==History==\nBorn in [[San Jose, California]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/2014/03/06/sxsw-music-picks-chain-gang-of-1974-buzzes-into-texas/|title=SXSW Music Picks: Chain Gang of 1974 buzzes into Texas|date=2014-03-06|website=The Mercury News|access-date=2017-08-01}}</ref> and raised in Hawaii (before moving to [[Denver]]), Kamtin Mohager (Nato) joined [[3OH!3]] as a touring bassist from 2008 through 2010. He self-released ''Fantastic Nostalgic: The Early Recordings'' in 2010. That year also saw the release of his full-length debut, ''White Guts''. Mohager moved to Los Angeles to record the follow-up album, ''Wayward Fire'', which was released on Modern Art Records in 2011.<ref name=\"Cherrie\">\n{{cite web\n| last=Cherrie\n| first=Chrysta \n| url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/the-chain-gang-of-1974-mn0001035500/biography\n| title=The Chain Gang of 1974 \u2013 Biography\n| website=[[Allmusic]]\n| accessdate=October 2, 2013\n}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2010, Mohager combined both early EP's into a digital-only release titled 'Fantastic Nostalgic: The Early Recordings. Mohager describes his early sound as \"all over the place, from a piano ballad to songs that sound like [[Black Rebel Motorcycle Club]], [[Primal Scream]], or [[Justice (band)|Justice]].\"<ref name=\"Fairbanks\">\n{{cite web\n| url=https://www.npr.org/2011/12/22/144067881/the-chain-gang-of-1974-on-world-cafe\n| title=The Chain Gang of 1974 on World Cafe\n| publisher=[[NPR]]\n| date=December 22, 2011\n| accessdate=October 2, 2013\n}}</ref> Zachary Houle of ''[[PopMatters]]'' called the album \"an homage to the '80s, in particular, the soundtracks to John Hughes films, and it is, in a word, fun.\"<ref name=\"Houle\">\n{{cite magazine\n| last=Houle\n| first=Zachary\n| url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/144925-the-chain-gang-of-1974-wayward-fire/\n| title=Review: The Chain Gang of 1974 \u2013 'Wayward Fire'\n| magazine=[[PopMatters]]\n| date=July 27, 2011\n| accessdate=October 2, 2013\n}}</ref> [[Pitchfork Media]]'s Ian Cohen remarked that it \"ends up less like a living celebration of the past and more like a display case of your favorite synth-pop action figures in their original packaging.\"<ref name=\"Cohen\">\n{{cite web\n| last=Cohen\n| first=Ian\n| url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/15644-wayward-fire/\n| title=Reviews: The Chain Gang of 1974 \u2013 'Wayward Fire'\n| publisher=[[Pitchfork Media]]\n| date=July 14, 2011\n| accessdate=October 2, 2013\n}}</ref> David Marchese of ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' wrote that the album \"swoons and grooves deliciously, but the lyrics have a distinctly processed flavor\".<ref name=\"Marchese\">\n{{cite journal \n| date=July 2011\n| last=Marchese\n| first=David\n| title=Reviews: Albums: The Chain Gang of 1974 \u2013 'Wayward Fire'\n| journal=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]\n| publisher=SPIN Media LLC\n| volume=27\n| issue=6\n| pages=70\u20131\n| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HjzFlV6oDIQC&pg=PA70&dq=%22chain+gang+of+1974%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=XHFMUvSLJuWiigLS6oC4Dg&ved=0CEIQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=%22chain%20gang%20of%201974%22&f=false\n| accessdate=October 2, 2013\n| issn=0886-3032}}</ref> Max Blau of ''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]'' called it \"one of the better and most cohesive electronic albums\" of 2011.<ref name=\"Blau\">\n{{cite magazine\n| last=Blau \n| first=Max\n| url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2011/06/best-of-whats-next-the-chain-gang-of-1974.html\n| title=Best of What's Next: The Chain Gang of 1974\n| magazine=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]\n| date=June 20, 2011\n| accessdate=October 2, 2013\n}}</ref> [[Allmusic]]'s William Ruhlmann said: \"Mohager convincingly makes the case that there is more to say in the music of the '80s, even if fashion has banished it to its own radio formats and nostalgia tours.\"<ref name=\"Ruhlmann\">\n{{cite web\n| last=Ruhlmann\n| first=William \n| url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/wayward-fire-mw0002137234\n| title=Album Review: The Chain Gang of 1974 \u2013 'Wayward Fire'\n| website=Allmusic\n| accessdate=October 2, 2013\n}}</ref> Justin Gerber of ''[[Consequence of Sound]]'' found flaws in the lyrics and suggested that \"just about every song could be cut by about a minute\", but added that \"nearly every song has a beat that pummels you into submission, and that is most definitely a compliment.\"<ref name=\"Gerber\">\n{{cite magazine\n| last=Gerber\n| first=Justin\n| url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2011/06/album-review-the-chain-gang-of-1974-wayward-fire/\n| title=Album Review: The Chain Gang of 1974 \u2013 'Wayward Fire'\n| magazine=[[Consequence of Sound]]\n| date=June 21, 2011\n| accessdate=October 2, 2013\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Mohager signed to [[Warner Music Group]] for the release of his third full-length album, ''[[Daydream Forever]]''. The album is described as a continuation of the synth-heavy, reverb-laden dreams that made Mohager\u2019s debut album, Wayward Fire, an immediate favorite of the retro set. Production is thicker here, with more elastic bounces. If that means it feels like you\u2019ve stepped into a 1980s night at the local bar (as one reviewer humorously put it), then Mohager has clearly succeeded. This is the guy who wasn\u2019t moved to make music until hearing [[Tears for Fears]] in the movie ''[[Real Genius]]'', says the legend; when tracks such as \u201cOrdinary Fools,\u201d \u201cYou,\u201d \u201cMoksha,\" and \u201cDeath Metal Punk\u201d hit you firmly across the ears with their indelible 1980s-styled hooks, everything is working according to his lo-hi-tech plans. Elements of [[Tears for Fears]], [[Duran Duran]], OMD, and [[M83 (band)|M83]] coalesce into a party of their own. \u201cPlum\u201d ends things on a slightly darker Prefab Sprout\u2013style tone.\n\nIn 2013, Mohager received worldwide recognition when his song \u201cSleepwalking\u201d was featured on the soundtrack of ''[[Grand Theft Auto V]]'', as well as on the game's official trailer.\n\nIn summer 2014, Mohager teamed up with DJ/producer [[Dillon Francis]], as well as [[Sultan & Ned Shepard]] for the release of \"When We Were Young\".<ref>{{youtube|95-cScAf_40|When We Were Young}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2015, Mohager launched a collaborative side project with Marshall Gallagher of [[Swing Hero]] titled \"[[Teenage Wrist]]\". The band's debut single \"Afterglow\" received praise from [[My Chemical Romance]] frontman [[Gerard Way]].\n\n===2016\u20132018: ''Felt''===\nOn September 9, 2016, The Chain Gang of 1974 released his single \"I Still Wonder\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=r9rh7wI3BRE |title=The Chain Gang of 1974 - I Still Wonder - YouTube |publisher=YouTube.com |date=September 9, 2016 |accessdate=2016-12-01}}</ref> On March 26, 2017, The Chain Gang of 1974 announced the release of his new album, ''[[Felt (The Chain Gang of 1974 album)|Felt]]'', which was released on June 23 through Caroline Records.\n\n===2019-Present: ''Pollen & Upcoming Album''===\nOn February 15, 2019, The Chain Gang of 1974 released the single \u201cBurn Out\u201d along with the announcement that he would be releasing one single per month throughout 2019. Then, on March 22, 2019, Mohager released \u201cHeaven\u201d, produced by [[Chadwick Johnson]] of the band Hundreth. The next month on April 26 followed the release of the third single, \u201cSuch A Shame.\u201d Mohager later stated on [[Twitter]] that the track was inspired by [[Jimmy Eat World]]. On May 24, The Chain Gang of 1974 released the fourth single \u201cOrdinary Fools, Pt. 2\u201d, the follow up to the [[Daydream Forever]] opening track \u201cOrdinary Fools\u201d. On June 21, Mohager released the track \u201cYDLMA\u201d (You Don\u2019t Love Me Anymore). The next month on July 26 saw the release\nOf \u201cFrom Here Who Knows\u201d. This was the last monthly single, and there was not another single in August. Instead of releasing a single in August, Mohager instead announces an upcoming [[Extended play|EP]] entitled \u201cPollen\u201d. The album would consist of the earlier singles \u201cHeaven\u201d, \u201cBurn Out\u201d, and \u201cOrdinary Fools, Pt. 2\u201d, along with a new song titled \u201cHide Tonight\u201d. The EP was released September 6, 2019. Later next month, Mohager announced a new album, and also stated the album would be coming sometime in 2020. The album title is still unknown, but the word \u201cHoney\u201d can be seen as part of the album title in Mohager\u2019s [[Instagram]] story. The album will have 12 tracks, and the remaining singles that weren\u2019t on the \u201cPollen\u201d EP would be included on the album. \u201cSuch A Shame\u201d, \u201cYDLMA\u201d, and \u201cFrom Here Who Knows\u201d. Also, Mohager released \u201c20:25\u201d, a collaborative Single with [[Flux Pavillon]] and [[whatsonot]].\n\n==Tour history==\nThe Chain Gang of 1974 has toured alongside bands, including [[AFI (band)|AFI]], [[Foster the People]], [[The Naked and Famous]], [[Washed Out]], [[Cibo Matto]], [[ABC (band)|ABC]], [[Big Audio Dynamite]], [[Tapes 'n Tapes]], [[Empires (band)|Empires]], [[Sir Sly]], [[Miniature Tigers]], and [[Geographer (band)|Geographer]].\n\n* [[Monolith Festival]] (2008)\n* [[Lollapalooza]] (2011)\n* [[Governors Ball Music Festival]] (2014)\n* [[Austin City Limits Music Festival]] (2014)\n* [[Capitol Hill Block Party]] (2014)\n* [[Free Press Summer Fest]] (2014)\n\n==Touring members==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n*Adam Halferty - drums, bass <small>(2008, 2011)</small>\n*Brandon Anamier \u2013 drums <small>(2008\u20132013)</small>\n*Justin Renaud \u2013 guitar <small>(2010\u20132011, 2016)</small>\n*Tyler Venter \u2013 bass <small>(2010\u20132011)</small>\n*Michael Spear \u2013 bass <small>(2011)</small>\n*Jeff Appruzzese - bass <small>(2011)</small>\n*Xander Singh - bass <small>(2011)</small>\n*Rob Pera - guitar, bass <small>(2011-2012)</small>\n*Jacob Bond \u2013 guitar <small>(2011\u20132014)</small>\n*Sam Tiger \u2013 bass <small>(2012\u20132014)</small>\n*Luc Laurent \u2013 drums <small>(2013\u20132014)</small>\n*Eric Halvorsen \u2013 bass <small>(2016-2017)</small>\n*Mike Robinson \u2013 drums <small>(2016-2017)</small>\n*Troupe Gammage - guitar <small>(2017)</small>\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Discography==\n* ''The Dirt EP'' (February 24, 2007)\n* ''When The Apple Drops - EP'' (January 16, 2008)\n* ''Fantastic Nostalgic: The Early Recordings'' (January 31, 2010)\n* ''White Guts'' (April 27, 2010)\n* ''Wayward Fire'' (June 21, 2011)\n* ''[[Daydream Forever]]'' (February 4, 2014)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/CHAINGANGOF1974/status/404683389644464128 |title=Twitter / CHAINGANGOF1974: New album//DAYDREAM |publisher=Twitter.com |date=November 24, 2013 |accessdate=2014-02-04}}</ref>\n* ''[[Felt (The Chain Gang of 1974 album)|Felt]]'' (June 23, 2017)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/CHAINGANGOF1974/status/845314050837774336 |title=Twitter / CHAINGANGOF1974: the new album FELT |publisher=Twitter.com |date=March 24, 2017 |accessdate=2017-03-25}}</ref>\n* ''Pollen - EP'' (September 6, 2019)\n\n==Songs in media==\n* Song \"Make My Body\" featured in ''[[Scream 4]]'' (2011).\n* Song \"Hold On\" featured in ''[[FIFA 12]]'' (2011).\n* Song \"Devil Is a Lady\" featured in ''[[FIFA Street (2012 video game)|FIFA Street]]'' (2012) and ''[[MLB 12: The Show]]'' (2012).\n* Song \"Undercover\" featured in ''[[FIFA Street (2012 video game)|FIFA Street]]'' (2012).\n* Song \"[[Sleepwalking (The Chain Gang of 1974 song)|Sleepwalking]]\" featured in ''[[Grand Theft Auto V]]'': The Official Trailer, can be heard in the game itself as radio music, and on the [[The Music of Grand Theft Auto V|official soundtrack]]. In addition to this, \"Sleepwalking\" is symbolically played as the end game credits theme for one of the game's three endings, mainly ending \"B\" (2013).\n* Song \"Miko\" featured in ''[[FIFA 14]]'' (2013).\n* Song \"You\" featured in ''[[Real World: Ex-Plosion]]'' (2014).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1243955/|title=The Shortcut (2009) |publisher=IMDb|accessdate=December 27, 2009}}\n*{{cite news|url=http://www.coloradodaily.com/ci_13125380|title=Club Notes: Back on the Chain Gang|last=Kale|first=Wendy |date=June 17, 2009|work=Colorado Daily|accessdate=December 27, 2009}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://clubnotes.pmpblogs.com/colorado-bands/chain-gang-of-1974-playing-bass-wi/|title=The Chain Gang of 1974: Playing Bass with 3OH!3 and Making Waves with Solo Project|last=Kale|first=Wendy |date=June 18, 2009|work=Colorado Daily Blogs|accessdate=December 27, 2009}}\n*{{cite news|url=http://www.kaffeinebuzz.com/interviews-the-chain-gang-of-1974.php|title=The Chain Gang of 1974 \u2013 playing Sunday, Sept 14, 1:30PM, GigBot Stage|last=Owens|first=Kim|date=September 12, 2008|work=Kaffeine Buzz|accessdate=December 27, 2009}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://royalflushmagazine.com/2009/01/22/3oh3-innerpartysystem-chaingang1974/|title=3OH!3, Inner Party System and The Chain Gang of 1974|last=Nubi|first=Lil|date=January 22, 2009|work=Royal Flush|accessdate=December 27, 2009}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/denver/events/white-tie-affair-every-avenue-stereo-skyline-runne,125061/|title=The White Tie Affair|date=November 20, 2009 |publisher=A. V. Club Denver/Boulder|accessdate=December 27, 2009}}{{refend}