70\n*[[May 16]] \u2013 [[Jean Antoine Zinnen]], composer of the Luxembourg national anthem, 71\n*[[August 17]] \u2013 [[Karl Zeller]], Austrian composer, 56 (pneumonia)\n*[[August 21]] \u2013 [[Niccol\u00f2 van Westerhout]], composer, 40 (peritonitis)\n*[[September 9]] \u2013 [[William Chatterton Dix]], hymn-writer, 61\n*[[September 11]] \u2013 [[Adolphe Samuel]], Belgian composer, 74\n*[[November 7]] \u2013 [[Max Alvary]], operatic tenor, 42\n*[[December 13]] \u2013 [[George Frederick Bristow]], composer, 72\n*[[December 29]] \u2013 [[Georg Goltermann]], cellist and composer, 74\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[1898]]\n* [[list of years in music]]\n\n[[Category:1898 in music| ]]\n[[Category:19th century in music]]\n[[Category:Music by year]]\n", "name_user": "Aklein62", "label": "safe", "comment": "Correction.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1898_in_music"}
{"title_page": "Darryl Reynolds", "text_new": "{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Darryl Reynolds\n| image  =File:Darryl Reynolds.jpg\n| caption = \n| number = 45\n| position = [[Forward (basketball)|Forward]]\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 9\n| weight_lbs = 240\n| league = \n| team = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1993|10|13}}\n| birth_place = [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]]\n| nationality = American\n| high_school = [[Lower Merion]] ([[Ardmore, Pennsylvania]])\n| college = [[Villanova Wildcats men's basketball|Villanova]] (2013\u20132017)\n| draft_year = 2017\n| career_start = 2017\n| years1 = 2017\u20132018\n| team1 = [[Start Lublin]]\n| cyears1 = 2018\u20132019\n| cteam1 = [[Villanova Wildcats men's basketball|Villanova]] (Director of Player Development)\n| highlights =\n*[[List of NCAA Men's Division I Basketball champions|NCAA champion]] ([[2016 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|2016]])\n}}\n'''Darryl Nasir Reynolds''' (born October 13, 1993) is an American [[basketball]] coach and former player. He played one season for [[Start Lublin]] in the [[Polish Basketball League]]. He played [[college basketball]] for the Villanova Wildcats.\n\n==Early life and high school career==\nReynolds was born in Philadelphia, the son of Rabia Sulayman and Darryl Reynolds, Sr. His siblings are Lailah, Malikah, Milan and Cannon. He attended [[Lower Merion High School]] and played AAU Basketball 1st for the Sharon Knights AAU then for Philly Pride.<ref name=\"villanova\">{{cite web|title=45 Darryl Reynolds|url=http://www.villanova.com/sports/m-baskbl/mtt/darryl_reynolds_852467.html|website=[[Villanova Wildcats]]|accessdate=June 28, 2017}}</ref> Coming into his senior season, his best college offer was Division II [[Holy Family University]], but as the season went on he began to get Division I looks.<ref name=\"jensen\">{{cite news|last1=Jensen|first1=Mike|title=Jensen: Darryl Reynolds' journey to Villanova senior standout unlike any other|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/sports/philly-hoops/20170312_Jensen__Darryl_Reynolds__journey_to_Villanova_senior_standout_unlike_any_other.html|accessdate=June 28, 2017|work=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]|date=March 12, 2014}}</ref> As a senior in 2011\u201312, he averaged 11.2 points, 8.2 rebounds and 4.2 blocked shots per game, improving those numbers to 15 points, 11 rebounds and 5.3 blocks in the PIAA playoffs. He led the Aces to Pennsylvania Class AAAA state championship game and was a first-team All-Central League and first-team All-Main Line selection. Reynolds did a postgraduate year at the [[Worcester Academy]], where he led the Hilltoppers to a 21\u20136 record. He signed with Villanova in April 2013 after considering [[Seton Hall Pirates men's basketball|Seton Hall]], [[Utah Utes men's basketball|Utah]], and [[South Carolina Gamecocks men's basketball|South Carolina]], choosing the Wildcats because he liked coach [[Jay Wright (basketball)|Jay Wright]] and the style of play.<ref name=\"dailytimes\">{{cite news|last1=Adams|first1=Bruce|title=From Lower Merion to Villanova, Darryl Reynolds writing fairy tale finish|url=http://www.delcotimes.com/article/DC/20170316/SPORTS/170319747|accessdate=June 28, 2017|work=[[Delaware County Daily Times]]|date=March 16, 2017}}</ref> Jay Wright began to notice him after [[Larry Brown (basketball)|Larry Brown]] pointed him out at a Chester-Lower Merion game when Wright was scouting [[Rondae Hollis-Jefferson]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Frank|first1=Reuben|title=Larry Brown To Thank For Villanova Discovering Darryl Reynolds|url=http://www.csnphilly.com/ncaa/larry-brown-thank-finding-villanovas-darryl-reynolds|accessdate=June 28, 2017|work=CSN Philly|date=April 2, 2016}}</ref> When [[Markus Kennedy]] transferred to [[SMU Mustangs men's basketball|SMU]], Reynolds was given a scholarship offer.<ref name=\"jensen\"/>\n\n==College career==\nReynolds played sparingly his freshman year, averaging 0.3 points and 1.0 rebounds in 3.1 minutes per game. He began to see more playing time in the non-conference season of his sophomore campaign, contributing six points, four rebounds and two blocked shots in a matchup against [[Saint Joseph's Hawks men's basketball|Saint Joseph's]]. Reynolds averaged 1.4 points and 1.2 rebounds in 5.4 minutes per game as a sophomore.<ref name=\"villanova\"/> He benefited in practicing against [[JayVaughn Pinkston]], who taught him how to be a more physical player. \"I had to learn how to play a lot harder,\" Reynolds said.<ref name=\"jensen\"/>\n\nAs a junior, Reynolds was a key reserve on the national championship-winning team. He set a new career high for rebounds with 13 in an 83\u201358 victory over [[Creighton Bluejays men's basketball|Creighton]] on February 3, 2016.<ref name=\"villanova\"/> With [[Daniel Ochefu]] injured, Reynolds scored a career-high 19 points to go with 10 rebounds in a 72\u201360 win against [[Providence Friars men's basketball|Providence]] on February 6.<ref>{{cite news|title=No. 3 Villanova too much for No. 11 Providence in 72-60 win|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400840301|accessdate=June 28, 2017|work=ESPN|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=February 6, 2016}}</ref> Consequently, he was named to the [[Big East]] Honor Roll for the week of February 8.<ref name=\"villanova\"/> The next game, Reynolds notched 14 points and six rebounds in an 86\u201359 win over [[DePaul Blue Demons men's basketball|DePaul]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Villanova cruises by DePaul 86-59 in 1st game as No. 1 team|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400840243|accessdate=June 28, 2017|work=ESPN|agency=Associated Press|date=February 9, 2016}}</ref> He played in all six NCAA Tournament wins, with his best effort coming in the Sweet 16 with eight points and five rebounds in a 92\u201369 win over [[Miami Hurricanes men's basketball|Miami]]. On the season, Reynolds averaged 3.6 points and 4.5 rebounds in 17.1 minutes per game.<ref name=\"villanova\"/>\n\nWith the graduation of Ochefu, Reynolds entered the starting lineup as a senior. In a 79\u201376 victory against [[Purdue Boilermakers men's basketball|Purdue]] on November 14, he had 12 points and eight rebounds.<ref>{{cite news|title=No. 3 Villanova needs Hart to get past No. 15 Purdue, 79-76|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400915183|accessdate=June 28, 2017|work=ESPN|agency=Associated Press|date=November 14, 2016}}</ref> On November 27, he added 12 points and eight rebounds in an 82\u201357 win over [[Pennsylvania Quakers men's basketball|Penn]], shooting 4-for-4 from the floor.<ref>{{cite news|title=No. 2 Villanova beats Penn 82-57 in latest city series romp|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400919331|accessdate=June 28, 2017|work=[[ESPN]]|agency=Associated Press|date=November 29, 2016}}</ref> The next game, he had a season-high 13 points to go along with six rebounds in an 88\u201357 win over Saint Joseph's. Reynolds's highest scoring game in Big East play was a 10-point effort in a victory over [[Xavier Musketeers men's basketball|Xavier]] on January 10, 2017.<ref name=\"villanova\"/> He missed five games with a rib injury but returned for the regular-season finale against [[Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball|Georgetown]], collecting seven rebounds and recording two steals in the 81\u201355 victory. In his senior year, Reynolds averaged 4.5 points and 5.4 rebounds in 23.8 minutes per game.<ref name=\"dailytimes\"/>\n\n==Professional career==\nReynolds participated in [[The Basketball Tournament 2017]] for the Villanova alumni team Supernova.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bailey |first1=Teddy |title=After NBA chance, Darryl Reynolds links up with Villanova greats |url=http://www2.philly.com/philly/sports/colleges/villanova/villanova-basketball-darryl-reynolds-the-basketball-tournament-tbt-20170712.html |accessdate=October 30, 2018 |work=[[Philadelphia Inquirer]] |date=July 12, 2017}}</ref> In August 2017 he signed with the Polish team Start Lublin.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.plk.pl/aktualnosci/n/16180/tbv-start-z-nowym-srodkowym.html| title = TBV Start z nowym \u015brodkowym| accessdate = August 17, 2017| publisher = plk.pl| language = Polish}}</ref> Reynolds averaged 8.6 points, 7.2 rebounds, and 1.3 blocks per game as the team made the Polish Cup for the first time in their history. In May 2018 Reynolds tore his ACL while playing a game on the La Salle campus. While recuperating, he created the \"Stay Tuned with D.Rey\" talk show in which he interviewed Villanova basketball players, alumni and faculty.<ref>{{cite web |title=Stay Tuned\u2019 with Darryl Reynolds |url=https://www.vuhoops.com/2018/10/29/18035314/stay-tuned-with-darryl-reynolds-a-talk-show-and-why-to-watch |website=VU Hoops |accessdate=October 30, 2018 |date=October 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\nIn 2018, Reynolds became the Director of Student Athlete Development at Villanova. He helped guide the team to a 26\u201310 record and Big East championship in the 2018\u201319 season.<ref>{{cite web |title=Darryl Reynolds - Men's Basketball Coach |url=https://villanova.com/sports/mens-basketball/roster/coaches/darryl-reynolds/1544 |website=[[Villanova Wildcats]] |accessdate=February 3, 2020}}</ref> In October 2019, he announced he was departing the coaching staff.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"So What\u2019s Next?\" for Villanova Basketball\u2019s Darryl Reynolds |url=https://www.vuhoops.com/villanova-basketball/2019/10/24/20930138/so-whats-next-by-villanova-basketball-darryl-reynolds-wildcats-jay-wright |website=VU Hoops |accessdate=February 3, 2020 |date=October 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/player/_/id/66174/darryl-reynolds ESPN profile]\n\n{{2016 Villanova Wildcats men's basketball navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Reynolds, Darryl}}\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American basketball players]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Poland]]\n[[Category:Basketball players at the 2016 NCAA Men's Division I Final Four]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Forwards (basketball)]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Start Lublin players]]\n[[Category:Villanova Wildcats men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Villanova Wildcats men's basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Lower Merion High School alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Darryl Reynolds\n| image  =File:Darryl Reynolds.jpg\n| caption = \n| number = 45\n| position = [[Forward (basketball)|Forward]]\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 9\n| weight_lbs = 240\n| league = \n| team = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1993|10|13}}\n| birth_place = [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]]\n| nationality = American\n| high_school = [[Lower Merion]] ([[Ardmore, Pennsylvania]])\n| college = [[Villanova Wildcats men's basketball|Villanova]] (2013\u20132017)\n| draft_year = 2017\n| career_start = 2017\n| years1 = 2017\u20132018\n| team1 = [[Start Lublin]]\n| cyears1 = 2018\u20132019\n| cteam1 = [[Villanova Wildcats men's basketball|Villanova]] (Director of Player Development)\n| highlights =\n*[[List of NCAA Men's Division I Basketball champions|NCAA champion]] ([[2016 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|2016]])\n}}\n'''Darryl Nasir Reynolds''' (born October 13, 1993) is an American [[basketball]] coach and former player. He played one season for [[Start Lublin]] in the [[Polish Basketball League]]. He played [[college basketball]] for the Villanova Wildcats.\n\n==Early life and high school career==\nReynolds was born in Philadelphia, the son of Rabia Sulayman and Darryl Reynolds, Sr. His siblings are Lailah, Malikah, Milan and Cannon. He attended [[Lower Merion High School]] and played AAU Basketball 1st for the Sharon Knights AAU then for Philly Pride.<ref na