         = \n| country               = [[China]]\n| administration        = \n| consecration_year     = \n| organisational_status = <!-- or | organizational_status = -->\n| functional_status     = \n| heritage_designation  = \n| ownership             = \n| governing_body        = \n| leadership            = \n| bhattaraka            = \n| patron                = \n| religious_features_label = \n| religious_features    = \n| architect             = \n| architecture_type     = \n| architecture_style    = \n| founded_by            = \n| creator               = \n| funded_by             = \n| general_contractor    = \n| established           = \n| groundbreaking        = \n| year_completed        = \n| construction_cost     = \n| date_demolished       = <!-- or | date_destroyed = -->\n| facade_direction      = \n| capacity              = \n| length                = \n| width                 = \n| width_nave            = \n| interior_area         = \n| height_max            = \n| dome_quantity         = \n| dome_height_outer     = \n| dome_height_inner     = \n| dome_dia_outer        = \n| dome_dia_inner        = \n| minaret_quantity      = \n| minaret_height        = \n| spire_quantity        = \n| spire_height          = \n| site_area             = \n| temple_quantity       = \n| monument_quantity     = \n| shrine_quantity       = \n| inscriptions          = \n| materials             = \n| elevation_m           = \n| elevation_footnotes   = \n| nrhp                  = \n| designated            = \n| added                 = \n| refnum                = \n| footnotes             = \n| website               = \n}}\n[[File:Jinjiang Cao'an 20120229-12.jpg|thumb|230px|Cao'an Temple seen from the south, with Huabiao Hill in the background]]\n'''Cao'an''' ({{zh|c=\u8349\u5eb5|p=C\u01ceo'\u0101n|poj=Chh\u00e1u-am|l=thatched nunnery}}<ref name=zayton>Samuel N.C. Lieu and Ken Parry, [http://www.mq.edu.au/research/centres_and_groups/ancient_cultures_research_centre/research/cultural_ex_silkroad/zayton/ Manichaean and (Nestorian) Christian Remains in Zayton (Quanzhou, South China). ARC DP0557098] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808000234/http://www.mq.edu.au/research/centres_and_groups/ancient_cultures_research_centre/research/cultural_ex_silkroad/zayton |date=2014-08-08 }}</ref>) is a temple in [[Jinjiang, Fujian]]. Originally constructed by [[Chinese Manichaeism|Chinese Manicheans]], it was considered by later worshipers as a [[Buddhist temple]].\nThis \"Manichean temple in Buddhist disguise\"<ref>Werner Sundermann, {{Iranica|manicheism-1-general-survey|MANICHEISM i. GENERAL SURVEY}}</ref>\nis seen by modern experts on Manichaeism as  \"the only extant Manichean temple in China\",<ref>Samuel N.C. Lieu, {{Iranica|chinese-turkestan-vii|CHINESE TURKESTAN: vii. Manicheism in Chinese Turkestan and China}}</ref> or \"the only Manichean building which has survived intact\".<ref name=\"Lieu 1992 256\u2013257\">{{harvnb|Lieu|1992|pp=256\u2013257}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Jinjiang Cao'an 20120229-06.jpg|thumb|Cao'an Temple main entrance]]\nThe temple is located on the southern slope of Huabiao Hill near Shedian Village just west of downtown Jinjiang.<ref name=li2006>Li Yukun (\u674e\u7389\u6606) [https://archive.is/20130221032440/http://www.51dh.net/magazine/html/342/342096.htm \u798f\u5efa\u664b\u6c5f\u8349\u5eb5\u6469\u5c3c\u6559\u9057\u5740] (The relics of Manichaean temple Cao'an in Jinjiang, Fujian), 2006</ref><ref>[[Google Maps]]</ref> Jinjiang is part of [[Quanzhou]], which was known historically as \"Quanzhou Prefecture\"; the location is some {{convert|50|km}} south of downtown Quanzhou.<ref name=\"Lieu 1992 256\u2013257\"/>\n\n[[He Qiaoyuan]] (1558-1632) explained in his local history, the ''Book of Fujian'' ({{zh|s=\u95fd\u4e66|p=''M\u01d0nsh\u016b''}}), that Huabiao Hill's name comes from the fact that it and the nearby Lingyuan Hill, look like a pair of [[huabiao]].<ref>{{harvnb|Lieu|1998|p=194}}</ref>\n\nThe temple as it exists today is not too different from a typical Buddhist temple of its region. It is a two-story [[granite]] building with the worship space downstairs and living space for a few priests upstairs.<ref name=Pearson2002>{{harvnb|Pearson|Li|Li|2002|pp=38\u201340}}, based on {{harvnb|Lieu|1980|pp=80\u201382}}</ref>\n\n==Background: Manichaeism in Fujian==\n{{see also|Religion in China#Manichaeism}} <!-- Manichaeism in China -->\n\nManichaeism arrived in China in 694 or earlier during the [[Tang dynasty]] (618-907). Early on, the Manichaean religion was strongly associated  with [[Sogdia]]n merchants, and, later, with [[Uyghurs]] resident in the Tang state. The religion was, however, primarily present in northern and central China (the [[Yangtze]] region) and suffered a strong setback during the anti-Manichaen campaign of 843, the prelude to the [[Great Anti-Buddhist Persecution]] of 845, when foreign Manichaean priests were exiled or executed.<ref>{{harvnb|Lieu|1992|pp=231\u2013239,263}}</ref>\n\nIt was in the 10th century, after the fall of the Tang, that Manichaeism, now primarily practised by [[Han Chinese]], reached Fujian. Its arrival in the province is linked to a certain Manichaean preacher who fled to Fujian from persecutions in [[North China]], traveled extensively throughout the province, and eventually died and was buried in Quanzhou Prefecture,<ref>{{harvnb|Lieu|1992|p=264}}</ref> which thus became one of the centers of [[Chinese Manichaeism]] during the [[Song dynasty]].<ref>{{harvnb|Lieu|1992|p=267}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Jinjiang Cao'an 20120229-03.jpg|thumb|left|General view of Cao'an Temple]]\nManichaeism in China assumed certain Chinese characteristics, assimilating to both [[Buddhism]] and [[Taoism]].<ref>{{harvnb|Mair|1987|p=316}}</ref> \nChinese translations of Manichaean treatises were couched in Buddhist phraseology,<ref>{{harvnb|Mair|1987|pp=317\u2013318}}</ref> and the religion's founder ([[Mar]]) [[Mani (prophet)|Mani]] (known in China as (\u672b)\u6469\u5c3c,  ''(Mo)-Mani'') received the title of the  \"Buddha of Light\" ({{zh|c=\u5149\u660e\u4f5b}} or {{lang|zh|\u5149\u4f5b}}), and a life story resembling that of [[Gautama Buddha]].<ref>{{harvnb|Lieu|1992|pp=243,255\u2013257}}</ref> At the same time, the Taoist (or pseudo-Taoist?) treatise, the ''[[Huahujing]]'' \"Scripture of the Conversion of the Barbarians\", popular with Chinese Manichaeans, declared Mani to be a reincarnation of [[Laozi]].<ref>{{harvnb|Lieu|1992|pp=258\u2013259}}.</ref>  As to the [[Confucianism|Confucian]] civil authorities of the Song state, when the clandestine cells of Mani's followers came to their attention, they were usually lumped together with assorted other suspicious and potentially troublesome sects as \"vegetarian demon worshipers\" ({{zh|\u5403\u83dc\u4e8b\u9b54}}).<ref>{{harvnb|Lieu|1992|pp=280\u2013283,298}}</ref>\n\nNot surprisingly, such Manichaean temples as were erected in Song China usually had an official Buddhist or Taoist affiliation.<ref>{{harvnb|Lieu|1992|pp=268}}</ref> There are records, for example, of a Manichaean temple in Taoist disguise at [[Siming District|Siming]]. This temple - one of the northernmost known Manichaean sites of the Song era - was established in the 960s, and was still active - in a more standard Taoist way, but with a memory of Manichaeism retained - in the 1260s.<ref>{{harvnb|Lieu|1992|pp=268,292\u2013294}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Jinjiang Cao'an 20120229-09.jpg|thumb|General view of the temple<!--\u8349\u5eb5\u5750\u4e1c\u671d\u897f\uff0c\u80cc\u4f9d\u5c71\u5ca9\uff0c\u5355\u6a90\u6b47\u5c71\u5f0f-->]]\nThe temple is said to have been initially constructed during the reign of [[Emperor Gaozong of Song]], the first emperor of the [[Southern Song]] (mid-12th century), as a straw hut. It was rebuilt in a more permanent way in the 5th year of the Zhiyuan era of [[Toghon Tem\u00fcr]] of the [[Yuan dynasty]] (1339).\n\nManichaeism in China became gradually extinct during the [[Ming dynasty|Ming]] and practically forgotten by the close of the Ming period; little material is available on the last centuries of the religion's existence. A short poem by Huang Fengxiang (d. 1614) tells about his visit to Cao'an Temple, which at the time had already been abandoned. The poet mentions Buddhist and Taoist symbols, but shows no awareness on its author's part of the temple's Manichaean origin.<ref>{{harvnb|Lieu|1992|p=303}}</ref>\n\nThe Quanzhou historian He Qiaoyuan left a short account of the shrine on Huabiao Hill and its Manichaean origin in the ''Book of Fujian'', which also gave him a reason to summarize what little he knew about the Manichaeans. This text is one of the few pieces of literary evidence we have from the last centuries of Manichaeism in China.<ref name=\"Lieu 1992 301\">{{harvnb|Lieu|1992|p=301}}</ref>  He Qiaoyuan speculated that there were still some followers of the \"Religion of Light\" ({{zh|c=\u660e\u6559}}) in Fujian in his days, but they \"[were] not much in evidence\" (\"\u4e0d\u751a\u663e\u4e91\").<ref name=\"Lieu 1992 301\"/><ref>The original text of the relevant section of ''Min Shu'', French translation, and detailed comments, can be found in {{harvnb|Pelliot|1923|pp=198\u2013207}}; English translation, in {{harvnb|Lieu|1998|pp=194\u2013195}}</ref>\n\nCao'an was renovated in 1922, becoming an annex of a Buddhist temple complex where the \"ancestral teachers of India and China\" were venerated; however, that temple complex later fell into disuse as well.<ref name=\"Lieu 1992 304\">{{harvnb|Lieu|1992|p=304}}</ref> As [[Samuel N.C. Lieu]] notes, worshipers at the time would probably think that the \"Moni\" moniker in Cao'an inscriptions referred to \"[\u015a\u0101kya]muni\" ([\u91ca\u8fe6]\u725f\u5c3c), i.e. Gautama Buddha;<ref name=\"Lieu 1992 304\"/> this is what the locals told archaeologist Wu Wenliang a few years later as well.<ref name=lieu1980/>\n\nAfter He Qiaoyuan's account of the Manichaean shrine was brought to the attention of modern scholars in 1923, by [[Chen Yuan (historian)|Chen Yuan]] ([[:zh:\u9648\u57a3|\u9648\u57a3]]) and [[Paul Pelliot]],<ref>{{harvnb|Pelliot|1923|p=198}}</ref> local researchers started looking for it. After a long search by a number of researchers (frustrated, at one point, by the presence of marauding bandits<ref name=zayton/>), it was finally identified with the existing building by the Quanzhou archaeologist Wu Wenliang (\u5434\u6587\u826f) in 1940,<ref>{{harvnb|Lieu|1992|p=304}}; Guo Zhichao (\u90ed\u5fd7\u8d85); the 1940 date is from [http://www.xmnn.cn/dzbk/xmwb/20070826/14.pdf \u4f5c\u4e3a\u6c11\u95f4\u4fe1\u4ef0\u7684\u6469\u5c3c\u6559 \u2014 \u664b\u6c5f\u8349\u5eb5\u9644\u8fd1\u6751\u793e\u7684\u6469\u5c3c\u6559\u53d8\u5f02\u9057\u5b58], 2007-08-26</ref> who presented the results of his on-site research in a 1957 publication.<ref name=lieu1980/>\n\nIn 1961, the temple was entered on the Fujian provincial list of protected cultural monuments; in 1996, it was added to China's [[Major national historical and cultural sites (Fujian)|National List of Historical and Cultural Sites, Fujian]].<ref name=li2006/>\n\n==Statuary and inscriptions==\n[[File:Jinjiang Cao'an 20120229-10.jpg|thumb|left|The Buddha of Light (Prophet Mani) carved from the [[rock-cut architecture|living rock]]]]\nThe most remarkable Manichaean relic in the temple is the statue of Manichaeism's founder [[Mani (prophet)|Mani]], commonly referred to in the Chinese Manichaean tradition as the \"Buddha of Light\". According to an [[Epigraphy|inscription]], the statue was donated to the temple by a local adherent in 1339.\n\nWhile the statue may look like any other Buddha to a casual observer, experts note a number of peculiarities which distinguish it from a [[Physical characteristics of the Buddha|typical portrayal]] of the Buddha. Instead of being curly-haired and clean-shaven, as most other Buddha statues, this Buddha of Light is depicted having straight hair draped over his shoulders, and sporting a beard. The facial features of the prophet (arched eyebrows, fleshy jowls) are somewhat different from a traditional Chinese stone Buddha as well.<ref name=\"Lieu 1992 256\u2013257\"/> It is even said that the stone Mani the Buddha of Light used to have a mustache or sideburns, but they were removed by a 20th-century Buddhist monk, trying to make the statue more like a traditional Buddha.<ref name=zayton/>\n\nInstead of looking down, as Buddha statues usually do, the Mani statue looks straight at the worshipers. Instead of being held in a typical [[Mudra#Common Buddhist mudr.C4.81s|Buddhist mudr\u0101]], Mani's hands rest on his belly, with both palms facing upward.<ref name=\"Lieu 1992 256\u2013257\"/>\n\n[[File:Jinjiang Cao'an 20120229-08.jpg|thumb|right|Restored inscription urging the faithful to remember \"Purity (\u6e05\u51c0), Light (\u5149\u660e), Power (\u5927\u529b), and Wisdom (\u667a\u6167)\", and \"[[Mani (prophet)|Moni]] (\u6469\u5c3c) the Buddha of Light (\u5149\u4f5b)\"]]\n\nIn order to give the statue an overall luminous impression, the sculptor carved its head, body, and hands  from stones of different hues.<ref name=\"Lieu 1992 256\u2013257\"/>\n\nInstead of a [[nianfo]] phrase, universally seen in China's Buddhist temples,<ref name=lieu1980>{{harvnb|Lieu|1980|pp=80\u201382}}</ref> an inscription on a stone in the courtyard dated 1445 urges the faithful to remember \"Purity (\u6e05\u51c0), Light (\u5149\u660e), Power (\u5927\u529b), and Wisdom (\u667a\u6167)\", which are the four attributes of the Father of Light,<ref name=\"Lieu 1992 256\u2013257\"/> one of the chief figures of the Manichaean pantheon.<ref>{{harvnb|Lieu|1998|p=136}}</ref> These four words (eight Chinese characters) were apparently an important motto of Chinese Manichaeism; it is described as such in an anti-Manichean work by the Fujianese Taoist [[Bo Yuchan]] (real name Ge Changgeng; ''[[floruit|fl]]''. 1215).<ref>{{harvnb|Lieu|1992|pp=291\u2013292}}</ref>\nThe original inscription was destroyed during the [[Cultural Revolution]], but later \"restored\" (apparently, on another rock).<ref name=zayton/>\n<!--\n{{\u5168\u56fd\u91cd\u70b9\u6587\u7269\u4fdd\u62a4\u5355\u4f4d\n|\u56fe\u7247 = [[File:Jinjiang Cao'an 20120229-01.jpg|210px]]\n|\u540d\u79f0 = \u8349\u5eb5\u77f3\u523b\n|\u7f16\u53f7 = 4-198\n|\u5206\u7c7b = \u77f3\u7a9f\u5bfa\u53ca\u77f3\u523b\n|\u65f6\u4ee3 = [[\u5143\u671d|\u5143]]\n|\u6240\u5728 = [[\u798f\u5efa\u7701]][[\u664b\u6c5f\u5e02]] \n|\u767b\u5f55 = 1996\u5e7411\u670820\u65e5\n}}\n\n\u8349\u5eb5\u59cb\u5efa\u4e8e[[\u5357\u5b8b]][[\u7ecd\u5174 (\u5e74\u53f7)|\u7ecd\u5174]]\u5e74\u95f4\uff0c\u5f53\u521d\u4ee5\u8305\u8349\u4f5c\u4e3a\u5efa\u7b51\u6750\u6599\u3002[[\u5143\u987a\u5e1d]][[\u81f3\u5143 (\u5143\u60e0\u5b97)|\u81f3\u5143]]\u4e94\u5e74\uff08[[1339\u5e74]]\uff09\uff0c\u7ecf\u7ffb\u4fee\u6539\u4e3a\u77f3\u7816\u74e6\u7ed3\u6784\uff0c\u6cbf\u7528\u8349\u5eb5\u539f\u540d\u3002\u8be5\u5efa\u7b51\u4e3a\u4e2d\u56fd\u552f\u4e00\u73b0\u5b58\u7684[[\u6469\u5c3c\u6559]]\u5bfa\u5e99\uff0c\n\n\u8349\u5eb5\u524d\u6709\u201c\u9690\u5c45\u6865\u201d\u3001\u201c\u516b\u51e4\u6c60\u201d\u3001\u201c\u5343\u5e74\u53e4\u6867\u201d\u7b49\u7f8e\u666f\u3002\u800c\u5728\u8349\u5eb5\u540e\u5c71\u6709\u76f8\u5f53\u591a\u7684\u6469\u5d16\u77f3\u523b\uff0c\u4e5f\u662f\u76f8\u5f53\u8457\u540d\u7684\u666f\u70b9\u5982\u201c\u4e07\u77f3\u5cf0\u201d\u201c\u7389\u6cc9\u201d\u3001\u201c\u4e91\u68af\u767e\u7ea7\u201d\u7b49\u6469\u5d16\u77f3\u523b\u3002\n-->\n<!-- {{clear}}\n{{Gallery\n|title=\n|footer=\n|width=240\n|height=\n|File:Jinjiang Cao'an 20120229-05.jpg|\u5efa\u5728\u4e00\u53f0\u5730\u4e0a\n}} \n-->\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{commons category|Cao'an}}\n* {{citation\n|first=Samuel N. C. |last=Lieu|publisher=Mohr Siebeck |year=1992|isbn=3161458206\n|title=Manichaeism in the Later Roman Empire and Medieval China\n|series=Volume 63 of Wissenschaftliche Untersuchungen Zum Neuen Testament\n|edition= 2\